            "author_info": {
                "name": "Stephen Milton",
                "href": "/profile/Stephen-Milton-2"
            },
            "answer_text": "Nope. They can\u2019t ban their adult child from owning a firearm. If the adult child\u2019s address is the parent\u2019s home, as in it\u2019s their official mailing address, they are also probably considered a tenant (regardless of if they pay any rent). If so, they also can\u2019t ban them from bringing said gun home\u2026it\u2019s their place of residence. Again, it\u2019s important to determine if the adult child is considered a tenant by state or local law\u2026if they ARE a tenant (again, regardless of rent\u2026 in the states I\u2019ve lived in, simply having it be your official mailing address is enough), they can ask the adult child to leave or not bring the firearm into the home but if the adult child insists, the only recourse is for the parents to being a formal eviction process. ",
            "date": "Answered October 27, 2020",
            "views": "34",
            "upvotes": "0"
        },
